What is Azure DNS?
Azure DNS is a DNS hosting service provided by Microsoft Azure that allows you to host your DNS domain in Azure and manage DNS records using Azure tools.

âœ… Azure DNS Use Cases
Use Case	Description
ğŸ”„ Domain name resolution	Resolve www.yourdomain.com to your app or VM IP
ğŸ¯ Custom domain mapping	Map your domain to App Service, Load Balancer, etc.
ğŸ“¦ Internal DNS (Private DNS)	Resolve names within VNet (for internal apps)
ğŸ” Secure routing	Use with Azure Front Door, App Gateway, Traffic Manager
ğŸ“¡ Hybrid DNS	Combine Azure Private DNS with on-prem DNS via DNS forwarding

ğŸ” DNS Types in Azure
Type	Description
ğŸŒ Azure DNS (Public)	For external name resolution (internet-facing)
ğŸ” Azure Private DNS	For internal name resolution within VNets

ğŸ› ï¸ Step-by-Step: Public DNS Setup in Azure
ğŸ“Œ Step 1: Register a Domain (Optional)
You can buy a domain from providers like GoDaddy, Namecheap, etc.

Or use an existing domain you own.

ğŸ“Œ Step 2: Create a DNS Zone
Using Azure Portal:
Search â†’ DNS Zones â†’ Click + Create

Select:

Subscription

Resource Group

Name: mydomain.com

Region: Global (no need to select)

Click Review + Create â†’ Create

Using Azure CLI:
bash
Copy
Edit
az network dns zone create \
  --name mydomain.com \
  --resource-group myResourceGroup
ğŸ“Œ Step 3: Add DNS Records
You can add:

Record Type	Purpose	Example
A Record	Maps domain to IPv4	app.mydomain.com â†’ 20.1.2.3
CNAME	Alias to another domain	www â†’ app.azurewebsites.net
MX	Mail server record	mail.mydomain.com
TXT	Verification / SPF	v=spf1 include:spf.protection.outlook.com

Add a CNAME or A Record (Portal):
Go to your DNS Zone â†’ Click + Record Set

Name: www

Type: CNAME

Value: mywebapp.azurewebsites.net

TTL: 3600 (default)

CLI Example (CNAME):
bash
Copy
Edit
az network dns record-set cname set-record \
  --resource-group myResourceGroup \
  --zone-name mydomain.com \
  --record-set-name www \
  --cname mywebapp.azurewebsites.net
ğŸ“Œ Step 4: Update Name Servers in Domain Registrar
After creating the DNS Zone, Azure gives 4 NS (Name Server) records.

ğŸ”— Go to your domain provider (like GoDaddy):

Find DNS settings

Replace existing NS records with Azureâ€™s NS values

e.g., ns1-02.azure-dns.com

â³ Propagation time: DNS changes may take up to 48 hours globally.

ğŸ“Œ Step 5: Test DNS Resolution
bash
Copy
Edit
